\f0\b \cf2 \outl0\strokewidth-182 \
WIN/LOSE CONDITIONS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0 \cf2 \outl0\strokewidth-182 \
As anyone familiar with endless runners will understand, there is no real way to \'93win\'94 a game like this. Put another way, the only way to win is to lose. That is to say, on a long enough timeline, CYBERBIKER players will 
\f1\i \outl0\strokewidth-182 always
\f0\i0\b \outl0\strokewidth-182  
\f2\b0 \outl0\strokewidth-182 lose. It\'92s just a matter of how long they can survive. The longer a player can stay in the game, the higher their final score will be.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \outl0\strokewidth-182 CONTROL SCHEME\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0 \cf2 \outl0\strokewidth-182 As a mobile game, special consideration must be paid to the affordances/constraints of touchscreen devices. Furthermore, when designing gameplay mechanics, features, and systems, decisions must be filtered through these considerations. The more complex the gameplay or feature, the more potential there is for something to be lost in translation as the feature is abstracted into a touch-based interaction.\
\
All the more reason to abide by our 
\f0\b \outl0\strokewidth-182 Radical Simplicity
\f2\b0 \outl0\strokewidth-182  design pillar. This game is played by touching the screen in simple, gestural ways. The more the player has to learn in regards to these gestures, the more difficult (that is, \'93unfair\'94) the game will become. More on specific controls below.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \outl0\strokewidth-182 \
UI\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0 \cf2 \outl0\strokewidth-182 As with 
\f0\b \outl0\strokewidth-182 Control Scheme,
\f2\b0 \outl0\strokewidth-182  special consideration must be paid toward screen real estate. The more items in the HUD (+ buttons, on-screen prompts) the more of a drain on the player\'92s attention bandwidth. \
\
We can\'92t know how players will play the game (specifically, we don\'92t know if they are left handed or right handed or how they will arrange their fingers on the screen) so best effort must be made to make the experience as ambidextrous as possible. \
\
We also need to free up as much of the screen as possible and reduce the total amount of buttons.\
\
Below is a potential early stage UI layout. \
